---
import BlogPost from '../../../../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
import { BLOG_POSTS } from '../../../../data/blog';

const meta = BLOG_POSTS.find((p) => p.slug === 'foreign-national-dscr-loans')!;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Do I need a US Social Security Number to qualify for a Foreign National DSCR loan?',
    answer:
      'No. Foreign National DSCR loans are designed for non-US citizens who do not have a US SSN. Qualifying uses international credit equivalent (Equifax Canada, Experian UK, etc.), foreign income documentation, and asset reserves. An ITIN is helpful but not strictly required by every program.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What countries do you accept borrowers from?',
    answer:
      'Clout accepts Foreign National DSCR borrowers from most stable-economy countries with verifiable credit and banking systems — Canada, the United Kingdom, the European Union, Australia, and many Latin American and Asian countries. OFAC-sanctioned countries are excluded. Confirm a specific country with your AE before submission.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can a Foreign National DSCR loan be used for a short-term rental?',
    answer:
      'Yes — short-term rental (Airbnb, Vrbo) properties are eligible. Underwriting uses AirDNA or AllTheRooms data plus a 12-month operating history (if available) to compute the qualifying rent. Properties in markets without STR data may require a long-term rental comp instead.',
  },
];
---

<BlogPost
  slug={meta.slug}
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  category={meta.category}
  datePublished={meta.datePublished}
  dateModified={meta.dateModified}
  lead="A Foreign National DSCR loan lets non-US citizens buy US rental property without a US Social Security Number, US tax returns, or US credit history. The property qualifies on its own cash flow — the borrower documents identity, foreign credit equivalent, and reserves. It is the cleanest path for international investors entering the US rental market."
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <h2>What "foreign national" means in this context</h2>
  <p>
    A foreign national, for mortgage purposes, is a person who is not a US citizen, not a US
    permanent resident (green card holder), and does not maintain primary residence in the
    United States. The category includes Canadian snowbirds buying Florida property, UK and
    European investors buying short-term rentals, Latin American business owners diversifying
    into US real estate, and Asian investors building US portfolio exposure. ITIN holders are
    a related but distinct category — they have US tax identification and typically use
    different programs.
  </p>

  <h2>Why DSCR is the right vehicle for foreign-national investors</h2>
  <p>
    A foreign national investor has two structural problems with conventional US lending:
    they don't have US W-2 income, and they don't have US credit history. DSCR underwriting
    sidesteps both by qualifying on property cash flow rather than borrower income. The
    borrower still has to prove identity, source the down payment, and document reserves, but
    the qualifying logic moves to the property — which the borrower is buying precisely
    because it generates US-dollar cash flow.
  </p>

  <h2>What Clout typically requires</h2>
  <div class="key-stats">
    <div><span class="k">Max LTV (purchase)</span><span class="v">65–75%</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Reserves</span><span class="v">6–12 months PITIA</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Min DSCR</span><span class="v">1.0+ standard</span></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li>Valid passport (color copy, all signed pages).</li>
    <li>US visa or proof of legal entry (typically a B-1/B-2 stamp or ESTA confirmation for visa-waiver-country borrowers).</li>
    <li>Foreign credit report or international credit reference equivalent (Equifax Canada, Experian UK, etc.). Some programs accept three-tradeline letters of reference from international banks in lieu of a formal credit report.</li>
    <li>Source-of-funds documentation for down payment and reserves (12 months of foreign bank statements; wire transfer trail into US escrow).</li>
    <li>Foreign tax returns or equivalent (helpful but not always required since income isn't the qualifying basis).</li>
    <li>US bank account for closing (often required at funding; can be opened during the process).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Property eligibility</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Non-owner-occupied investment property only (rental purpose). No US primary residence.</li>
    <li>1–4 unit residential, condotel and condo with project review, short-term rental eligible in approved markets.</li>
    <li>Rural and non-warrantable condo files have additional review steps.</li>
    <li>LLC vesting allowed (most foreign-national investors prefer it).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common use cases at Clout</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Canadian investors buying Florida vacation rentals.</strong> Naples, Miami, Orlando, Tampa Gulf Coast. AirDNA-supported underwriting.</li>
    <li><strong>UK and European investors buying NY metro long-term rentals.</strong> Brooklyn brownstones, Jersey City multi-family, Long Island.</li>
    <li><strong>Latin American business owners buying Houston / Dallas single-family rentals.</strong> Long-term lease comps from MLS.</li>
    <li><strong>Asian investors entering Texas portfolio markets.</strong> San Antonio, Austin suburbs.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout">
    <p class="callout-title">Typical close timeline</p>
    <p>
      25–35 days from submission to clear-to-close. The international documentation, foreign
      credit translation, and source-of-funds reconciliation extend the timeline vs domestic
      DSCR. Plan offer-to-close around a 30-day window with a 5-day buffer.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Frequently asked</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    {faqs.map((f) => (
      <details>
        <summary>{f.question}</summary>
        <div><p>{f.answer}</p></div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>
  <p>
    Foreign national investors: <a href="/contact/">contact Clout</a> directly for an
    eligibility read. Mortgage brokers placing wholesale Foreign National files: open the
    <a href="/tpo-connect/">TPO Connect partner hub</a> or run a scenario through the desk. Related:
    <a href="/resources/blog/dscr-loans-real-estate-investors/">DSCR Loans for Real Estate Investors</a> ·
    <a href="/loan-options/foreign-national/">Foreign National program page</a> ·
    <a href="/resources/glossary/#foreign-national-mortgage">Foreign National</a> in the glossary.
  </p>
</BlogPost>
